DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Southland Corp. said it may be unable to makepayments due in 1991 on debt it incurred in its $4.9 billionleveraged buyout and is considering a recapitalization or otherrestructuring.   Southland, which was acquired by its founding Thompson family inthe 1987 buyout, until now had maintained that it could meet itsdebt obligations. But the company said Tuesday that salesprojections at its 7-Eleven convenience stores had not been met.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A House panel has approved a bill that givesthe Securities and Exchange Commission limited authority to controlprogram trading in market emergencies.   The telecommunications and finance subcommittee, after asometimes heated debate over whether it was moving too fast, votedTuesday to send the bill to the full Energy and Commerce Committeefor consideration, possibly as soon as Thursday.   The bill, known as the Securities Markets Stabilization Act of1989, would give the Securities and Exchange Commission newauthority to suspend or constrain practices that could cause marketvolatility _ sharp price rises and drops.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Dow Jones andamp; Co. Inc. said it is introducing aninteractive 900-number telephone service that will enable callersto get stock quotes, business and financial news, sports reportsand weather conditions.   Dow Jones, publisher of The Wall Street Journal, said Tuesday itplans to charge 85 cents for the first minute and 75 cents for eachadditional minute for calls to its service, called JournalPhone.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp. has reported a netloss of $447 million for the third quarter as income from itsdomestic cigarette business declined.   The loss, reported Tuesday, compared with a net profit of $355million, or $1.55 a share, in the third quarter of last year.   The consumer products giant was taken private in October 1988 ina $24.53 billion leveraged buyout by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts andamp; Co.Therefore, there are no per-share figures for the latest results.</TEXT><DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Delta Air Lines said it plans to buy $10 billionworth of new jets, including 160 of McDonnell Douglas Corp.'s newMD-90 aircraft.   The orders and options announced Tuesday are in addition to $13billion in plane orders announced earlier by the Atlanta-basedcarrier. Delta has orders and options now on a total of 519 newjets.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Former Wall Street stock speculator Ivan F.Boesky has been granted a temporary release from his three-yearterm at a California prison camp, authorities said.   Boesky is due back at the minimum-security prison in Lompoc,Calif., around the end of the month, said Ed Wolahan, the prison'ssupervisor of education. The furlough began Thursday.   Tuesday marked three years since Boesky paid $100 million andagreed to plead guilty to one felony to settle charges in WallStreet's biggest insider trading scandal.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stock prices retreated in sluggish trading Tuesday amiduneasiness about the economy's weakness and pessimism about thechances for lower interest rates. The Dow Jones industrial averagefell 16.18 to 2,610.25.   The dollar fell sharply against all key currencies.   Bond prices finished mixed.   Platinum futures prices climbed to six-month highs; gold andsilver also advanced; cocoa futures plunged; energy, livestock andmeat futures were lower; and grains and soybeans were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>